2026-04-21 01:31:48 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Load module series diode', 'Main lamp in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='Power is present: the supply LED is on, and measurements show correct polarity from the power‑supply positive through the control switch and cables up to the anode of the load‑module diode. Polarity between modules is correct and continuity from the control-module switched output to the diode anode is good (~0.1 Ω). The control-module fault indicator LED is off, consistent with correct polarity and absence of a short. Therefore, the only remaining elements in series with the supply and preventing current from reaching the lamp are inside the load module itself: the series diode and the lamp. \n\nIf the series diode is open-circuit (failed open, reversed installation, or broken connection), there will be no current to either the main lamp or the internal indicator lamp, so both remain off despite correct 12 V at the diode anode. An open main lamp alone would still allow the parallel small indicator bulb to light, so the absence of any lamp illumination strongly implicates the diode or its immediate connections rather than just the main bulb filament. \n\nThus the most probable root cause is an open or incorrectly oriented load‑module series diode (and its associated solder joints/wiring). The main lamp may also be defective, but the diode/open‑path fault must be corrected first to restore operation.'
